{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458141,"nonce":"gKPra4EoTgnJAz6UKT8vVJKyOLA=","title":"Part 2 analysis: feedback perturbation responses with SISU","message":"Umbrella: 0af472c (Part 2)\n\n**Motivation:** How does the SISU contextual input modulate the feedback correction loop? If the network uses SISU to anticipate perturbations, we expect SISU-dependent changes in feedback gain and correction dynamics, especially when comparing trained-robust vs trained-baseline models.\n\n**Approach:** Same impulse perturbation paradigm as Part 1 but now crossed with SISU levels. Computes aligned variables, scalar measures, and violin plots. Groups results by SISU, training perturbation std, and perturbation variable (position/velocity). Uses `lohi` to contrast extreme training conditions.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part2/feedback_perts.py`. Shares structure with Part 1 version but adds SISU dimension. Includes custom early-timestep measures (mean command/force at steps 1-2) for probing anticipatory adjustments. Note: marked as \"redundant with 1-2\" for some constants.\n\n**References:** Adapted from Part 1 feedback perturbation paradigm; Cluff \u0026 Scott (2013).","files":null}]}